{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17648180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17648180"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:51:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:51:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18298"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18298"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11016"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11016"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18298"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63856"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25571"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26894"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere is a muscle that laterally rotates the femur on the tibia to unlock the knee and so allowing flexion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is this muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrocnemius","Gracilis","Popliteus","Quadriceps femoris","Sartorius"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epopliteus\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is responsible for unlocking the knee joint by laterally rotating the femur on the tibia. This action is crucial for initiating knee flexion from a fully extended position, a process known as the screw-home mechanism. The popliteus muscle plays a vital role in stabilising the knee joint and allowing smooth transition between extension and flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Equadriceps femoris\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily responsible for knee extension and does not play a role in unlocking the knee.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrocnemius\u003C/strong\u003E muscle, while involved in knee flexion, does not contribute to the lateral rotation of the femur on the tibia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egracilis\u003C/strong\u003E is a muscle of the medial thigh that assists in hip adduction and knee flexion but does not affect the screw-home mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esartorius\u003C/strong\u003E muscle assists in flexing, abducting, and laterally rotating the hip, as well as flexing the knee, but it does not play a role in unlocking the knee joint.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The popliteus muscle is responsible for unlocking the knee by laterally rotating the femur on the tibia.","The screw-home mechanism is a key component of knee joint stability and movement.","Understanding the role of specific muscles in joint mechanics is crucial for diagnosing and managing musculoskeletal conditions."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63856"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18298"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63856"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T08:57:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T08:57:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11016"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.e